WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:21.280
Black Beauty by Anna Sewell

00:31.000 --> 00:34.000
Chapter 1

00:34.000 --> 00:38.000
My First Home

00:38.000 --> 00:43.000
I live in a big meadow with a pond and trees around it.

00:43.000 --> 00:47.000
During the day I run in the meadow with my mother,

00:47.000 --> 00:50.000
and at night I sleep next to her.

00:50.000 --> 00:54.000
There are six other cults in the meadow.

00:54.000 --> 00:58.000
I run with them too and have great fun.

00:59.000 --> 01:02.000
But sometimes they kick and bite me.

01:02.000 --> 01:05.000
My mother always says,

01:05.000 --> 01:10.000
These cults are good, but they're not polite.

01:10.000 --> 01:14.000
You come from a family of famous horses.

01:14.000 --> 01:18.000
You must always be good and gentle,

01:18.000 --> 01:22.000
and never bite or kick.

01:22.000 --> 01:27.000
My mother's name is Duchess, and she is old and wise.

01:28.000 --> 01:31.000
She is our master's favourite horse,

01:31.000 --> 01:36.000
and she always takes him to town in a small carriage.

01:36.000 --> 01:39.000
Our master is a kind man.

01:39.000 --> 01:43.000
He gives us a lot of oats, a big carrot,

01:43.000 --> 01:46.000
and a warm place to live.

01:46.000 --> 01:50.000
He always says nice things to us.

01:50.000 --> 01:53.000
Sometimes he gives us some sugar.

01:53.000 --> 01:56.000
We all love him.

01:56.000 --> 02:01.000
One day I see a lot of dogs running in another green meadow,

02:01.000 --> 02:05.000
and they are barking loudly.

02:05.000 --> 02:08.000
What's happening, mother? I ask.

02:08.000 --> 02:11.000
The dogs are running after a hair.

02:11.000 --> 02:14.000
She says, there is a hunt.

02:14.000 --> 02:19.000
The dogs run fast, and the hair does too.

02:19.000 --> 02:22.000
There is a lot of noise.

02:22.000 --> 02:27.000
Finally, the dogs catch the poor hair and kill it.

02:27.000 --> 02:31.000
Then another sad thing happens.

02:31.000 --> 02:36.000
Two horses and two men fall to the ground.

02:36.000 --> 02:41.000
One man gets up, but the other does not.

02:41.000 --> 02:44.000
The dogs are silent now,

02:44.000 --> 02:48.000
and everyone is looking at the man and the two horses.

02:48.000 --> 02:53.000
It's young George Gordon, the landowner's son.

02:53.000 --> 02:55.000
Says mother, sadly.

02:55.000 --> 02:59.000
The poor young man is dead.

02:59.000 --> 03:03.000
Only one horse gets up, but the other cannot,

03:03.000 --> 03:06.000
because his leg is broken.

03:06.000 --> 03:11.000
Someone runs to the master's house and gets a gun.

03:11.000 --> 03:17.000
There is a loud shot, and the horse is dead.

03:17.000 --> 03:22.000
I am four years old now, and I am a handsome cult.

03:22.000 --> 03:29.000
I have a nice black coat and a white star on my forehead.

03:29.000 --> 03:34.000
One day, the landowner, Mr. Gordon, comes to look at me.

03:34.000 --> 03:40.000
He looks at my eyes, my teeth, and my legs.

03:40.000 --> 03:44.000
When you break him in, I want to see him.

03:44.000 --> 03:46.000
Says Mr. Gordon.

03:46.000 --> 03:48.000
Very well, Mr. Gordon.

03:48.000 --> 03:50.000
Says my master.

03:50.000 --> 03:53.000
He smiles at me and says,

03:53.000 --> 03:56.000
Tomorrow, I must break you in.

03:56.000 --> 04:01.000
I must teach you to wear a saddle and bridle,

04:01.000 --> 04:05.000
and carry a person on your back.

04:05.000 --> 04:10.000
Then I must teach you to pull a carriage.

04:11.000 --> 04:14.000
Tomorrow is an important day.

04:14.000 --> 04:17.000
Says mother, quietly.

04:17.000 --> 04:22.000
Remember, you must always listen to your master,

04:22.000 --> 04:25.000
and never bite or kick.

04:25.000 --> 04:29.000
And you must never jump when you're happy,

04:29.000 --> 04:32.000
or stop when you're tired.

04:32.000 --> 04:37.000
Always be a good horse.

04:37.000 --> 04:42.000
The next day, my master comes and talks to me quietly.

04:42.000 --> 04:49.000
Then he gently puts the bit into my mouth and the bridle on my face.

04:49.000 --> 04:54.000
The bit hurts my mouth and feels terrible,

04:54.000 --> 04:59.000
but my mother and other adult horses wear it too.

04:59.000 --> 05:06.000
Then my master puts a saddle on my back and says kind words to me.

05:07.000 --> 05:13.000
He slowly gets on the saddle and rides me around the meadow.

05:13.000 --> 05:17.000
I am happy when I carry him.

05:17.000 --> 05:21.000
After some time, he takes me to the blacksmith.

05:21.000 --> 05:25.000
The blacksmith puts on horse shoes.

05:25.000 --> 05:31.000
They are very heavy metal shoes, and I do not like them.

05:31.000 --> 05:37.000
Today, we're going to visit my friend Simon, my master says.

05:37.000 --> 05:43.000
At Simon's house, I stay in a meadow with cows and sheep.

05:43.000 --> 05:50.000
Suddenly, a big train goes by, and it makes a lot of noise and smoke.

05:50.000 --> 05:56.000
I run to the other side of the meadow because I am afraid,

05:56.000 --> 06:01.000
but the cows and sheep do not move.

06:01.000 --> 06:09.000
A lot of trains go by, but they do not hurt me, so I am not afraid of them.

06:09.000 --> 06:17.000
Sometimes, I pull the carriage with my mother, and she teaches me a lot of things.

06:17.000 --> 06:22.000
There are many kinds of masters, she says.

06:22.000 --> 06:28.000
Some are good, but others are bad and cruel.

06:28.000 --> 06:36.000
You must always listen to them and remember the good name of your family.

06:36.000 --> 06:42.000
In May, one of Mr. Gordon's men comes and takes me away.

06:42.000 --> 06:46.000
My master says goodbye, my friend.

06:46.000 --> 06:51.000
Be a good horse and always do your best.

06:51.000 --> 06:57.000
I cannot say goodbye, so I put my nose in his hand.

06:57.000 --> 07:02.000
My new home at Mr. Gordon's is lovely.

07:02.000 --> 07:08.000
There is a big stable, and I have a comfortable stall.

07:08.000 --> 07:12.000
There is another horse in the next stall.

07:12.000 --> 07:17.000
Hello, what's your name? I ask.

07:17.000 --> 07:22.000
My name is Mary Legs, says the horse.

07:22.000 --> 07:26.000
I carry the young ladies on my back.

07:26.000 --> 07:29.000
Are you my new neighbor?

07:29.000 --> 07:33.000
Yes, I am. Do you bite?

07:33.000 --> 07:35.000
Asks Mary Legs.

07:35.000 --> 07:38.000
No, I don't, I answer.

07:38.000 --> 07:41.000
I only bite grass.

07:41.000 --> 07:43.000
Oh, good.

07:43.000 --> 07:49.000
Because the horse in the other stall sometimes bites, says Mary Legs.

07:49.000 --> 07:58.000
She's a brown horse, and her name is Ginger.

07:58.000 --> 08:03.000
Chapter 2, the bridge.

08:03.000 --> 08:09.000
My coachman's name is John Manley, and he lives near the stables.

08:09.000 --> 08:15.000
John is a friendly man, and he always gives me a good grooming.

08:15.000 --> 08:19.000
He is a good rider, too.

08:19.000 --> 08:21.000
Good morning, John.

08:21.000 --> 08:23.000
Says Mr. Gordon.

08:23.000 --> 08:25.000
How's the new horse?

08:25.000 --> 08:29.000
He's fast and easy to ride, sir.

08:29.000 --> 08:30.000
Says John.

08:30.000 --> 08:33.000
He comes from a good family.

08:33.000 --> 08:34.000
What's his name?

08:34.000 --> 08:36.000
Asks Mr. Gordon.

08:36.000 --> 08:40.000
I don't know, sir, says John.

08:40.000 --> 08:42.000
Well, he's a beauty.

08:42.000 --> 08:44.000
Says Mr. Gordon.

08:44.000 --> 08:48.000
Let's call him Black Beauty.

08:48.000 --> 08:53.000
I like my new name and my new master.

08:53.000 --> 08:56.000
After a few days, John says to me,

08:56.000 --> 09:01.000
Today you're going out on a carriage with Ginger.

09:01.000 --> 09:07.000
I am not happy about this, because Ginger is not friendly.

09:07.000 --> 09:12.000
But after a few rides in the carriage, we start talking.

09:12.000 --> 09:17.000
Sometimes I bite and kick, but I'm not a bad horse.

09:17.000 --> 09:20.000
Says Ginger, sadly.

09:20.000 --> 09:25.000
In my life, I can only remember cruel masters.

09:25.000 --> 09:28.000
Bad coachman, and the whip.

09:28.000 --> 09:32.000
Oh, I'm sorry, Ginger, I say.

09:32.000 --> 09:35.000
Are you happy here?

09:35.000 --> 09:37.000
Yes, I am.

09:37.000 --> 09:39.000
Says Ginger.

09:39.000 --> 09:43.000
Because the master and the coachman are both kind.

09:43.000 --> 09:46.000
They understand horses.

09:46.000 --> 09:52.000
Now we are good friends, and I like her a lot.

09:52.000 --> 09:58.000
They also like merry legs, because he is always happy and friendly.

09:58.000 --> 10:03.000
He is the favorite horse of Miss Jessie and Flora.

10:03.000 --> 10:07.000
They are Mr. Gordon's daughters.

10:07.000 --> 10:11.000
One cloudy autumn day, the master says,

10:11.000 --> 10:16.000
John, get the carriage ready with Black Beauty.

10:16.000 --> 10:20.000
We must go to town on business.

10:20.000 --> 10:26.000
This is the first time for me to go to town with the master and John.

10:26.000 --> 10:28.000
I am excited.

10:28.000 --> 10:33.000
I want to do my best, and please the master.

10:33.000 --> 10:42.000
The master and John are in the carriage, and it starts raining, and it is very windy.

10:42.000 --> 10:47.000
We get to town, and the master goes to see some people.

10:47.000 --> 10:51.000
John and I wait for him in the rain.

10:51.000 --> 10:55.000
When he finishes his business, he says,

10:55.000 --> 10:57.000
Let's go home, John.

10:57.000 --> 11:02.000
Perhaps we can cross the bridge before it is dark.

11:02.000 --> 11:05.000
It's a dangerous bridge when it rains.

11:05.000 --> 11:07.000
Says John.

11:07.000 --> 11:13.000
We take the country road to the bridge, and it is raining hard.

11:13.000 --> 11:18.000
I am very careful, because the road is bad.

11:18.000 --> 11:23.000
When my feet touch the bridge, I know something is wrong.

11:23.000 --> 11:27.000
I cannot move, and I stop.

11:27.000 --> 11:29.000
Go on, Black Beauty.

11:29.000 --> 11:31.000
Says my master.

11:31.000 --> 11:36.000
I cannot move, because I feel there is danger on the bridge.

11:36.000 --> 11:40.000
There's something wrong, sir, says John.

11:40.000 --> 11:46.000
Beauty doesn't want to cross the bridge, but we must cross the bridge.

11:46.000 --> 11:50.000
It's late, says the master.

11:50.000 --> 11:55.000
At that moment, a man runs out of his house and cries,

11:55.000 --> 12:00.000
Stop, stop, go back, don't cross the bridge.

12:00.000 --> 12:03.000
It's broken in the middle.

12:03.000 --> 12:05.000
Broken in the middle?

12:05.000 --> 12:06.000
Says the master.

12:06.000 --> 12:09.000
Oh, thank you, Black Beauty.

12:09.000 --> 12:13.000
Yes, thank you, Beauty.

12:13.000 --> 12:15.000
Says John.

12:15.000 --> 12:20.000
We take another country road and get home late.

12:20.000 --> 12:22.000
What a rainy night.

12:22.000 --> 12:25.000
Says the mistress when she sees us.

12:25.000 --> 12:28.000
I'm happy you're home.

12:28.000 --> 12:31.000
You can thank Black Beauty.

12:31.000 --> 12:34.000
He's a very wise horse.

12:34.000 --> 12:36.000
Says the master.

12:36.000 --> 12:44.000
That night, John dries my wet coat and puts on my warm blue blanket.

12:44.000 --> 12:50.000
Then he gives me a good dinner, and I can finally sleep.

12:50.000 --> 12:55.000
The next day, a new stable boy comes to work.

12:55.000 --> 13:01.000
His name is Joe Green, and he is 14 years old.

13:01.000 --> 13:07.000
I like him because he has a gentle hand, and he talks to me.

13:07.000 --> 13:14.000
One night, the stable bell rings loudly, and all the horses wake up.

13:14.000 --> 13:16.000
I hear John's voice.

13:16.000 --> 13:18.000
Beauty, wake up.

13:18.000 --> 13:24.000
The mistress is very ill, and we must go and find Dr. White.

13:24.000 --> 13:28.000
He puts a saddle on my back and gets on.

13:28.000 --> 13:33.000
I gallop fast because I want to help the mistress.

13:33.000 --> 13:37.000
It is a dark, cold night.

13:37.000 --> 13:41.000
When we get to Dr. White's house, John calls him.

13:41.000 --> 13:47.000
A window opens, and the doctor puts his head out and says,

13:47.000 --> 13:53.000
What's the matter at three o'clock in the morning?

13:53.000 --> 13:57.000
Mrs. Gordon is very ill, says John.

13:57.000 --> 14:00.000
Please come at once.

14:00.000 --> 14:03.000
Can I use your horse?

14:03.000 --> 14:05.000
asks the doctor.

14:05.000 --> 14:09.000
My horse has a bad leg.

14:09.000 --> 14:13.000
Yes, of course, says John.

14:13.000 --> 14:22.000
The doctor is a heavy man and not a good rider, but I do my best and gallop home.

14:22.000 --> 14:27.000
He runs to see the mistress, and Joe takes me to the stable.

14:27.000 --> 14:31.000
I am very wet and cold.

14:31.000 --> 14:36.000
Joe drives me and gives me some water and oats.

14:36.000 --> 14:40.000
But he forgets to put my warm blue blanket on.

14:40.000 --> 14:46.000
Soon I start shaking, and I am very cold.

14:46.000 --> 14:49.000
I feel terrible.

14:49.000 --> 14:54.000
The next day the master comes to see me.

14:54.000 --> 14:59.000
Thanks to you, Black Beauty, the mistress is feeling better.

14:59.000 --> 15:05.000
He says, But now you are ill, my poor beauty.

15:05.000 --> 15:09.000
We must call the vet at once.

15:09.000 --> 15:16.000
I am very ill now, but the master's kind words make me feel better.

15:20.000 --> 15:26.000
Chapter 3, Lord and Lady Wadsworth.

15:26.000 --> 15:32.000
My life at Mr. Gordon's is happy, but things are changing.

15:32.000 --> 15:38.000
The mistress is ill, and the master is sad and worried.

15:38.000 --> 15:42.000
Dr. White comes here often and says,

15:42.000 --> 15:49.000
Mrs. Gordon must go to warm country for two or three years.

15:49.000 --> 15:53.000
Then perhaps she can get better.

15:53.000 --> 15:59.000
Everyone is sad, because we must soon say goodbye.

15:59.000 --> 16:03.000
One day Jesse and Flora come to the stable.

16:03.000 --> 16:05.000
Goodbye dear Mary Lex.

16:05.000 --> 16:07.000
They say.

16:07.000 --> 16:11.000
Thank you for all the wonderful rights.

16:11.000 --> 16:14.000
They hug him like an old friend.

16:14.000 --> 16:17.000
Don't be sad, Mary Lex.

16:17.000 --> 16:19.000
Says Jesse.

16:19.000 --> 16:22.000
Father is selling you to the old vicar.

16:22.000 --> 16:27.000
He is a kind man and loves horses.

16:27.000 --> 16:34.000
Then the master comes to the stable and talks to Ginger and me.

16:34.000 --> 16:38.000
I am selling you to Lord Wadsworth.

16:38.000 --> 16:42.000
He's a good man and lives in the country.

16:42.000 --> 16:45.000
Goodbye black beauty and Ginger.

16:45.000 --> 16:49.000
He pats us on the neck for a long time.

16:49.000 --> 16:55.000
I cannot say goodbye, so I put my nose in his hand.

16:55.000 --> 17:01.000
Ginger and I are very sad to leave our master and our stable.

17:01.000 --> 17:06.000
But this is the life of a horse.

17:06.000 --> 17:13.000
Lord Wadsworth has a beautiful house with a green meadow and big stables.

17:13.000 --> 17:19.000
John and our new coachman, Mr. York, take us to our stalls.

17:19.000 --> 17:23.000
He looks at us carefully and says.

17:23.000 --> 17:27.000
They look like very good horses, Mr. Manley.

17:27.000 --> 17:30.000
What can you tell me about them?

17:30.000 --> 17:35.000
Black beauty is gentle and wise and always does his best.

17:35.000 --> 17:37.000
Says John.

17:37.000 --> 17:40.000
He is also very fast.

17:40.000 --> 17:46.000
Ginger's a good horse too, but sometimes she's nervous.

17:46.000 --> 17:49.000
Do they wear the bearing rain?

17:49.000 --> 17:51.000
asks Mr. York.

17:51.000 --> 17:53.000
No they don't.

17:53.000 --> 17:55.000
Says John.

17:55.000 --> 17:56.000
Well.

17:56.000 --> 17:57.000
Says Mr. York.

17:57.000 --> 17:59.000
Here they must wear it.

17:59.000 --> 18:04.000
The Lord and I like a soft rain, but Lady Wadsworth wants the bearing rain.

18:04.000 --> 18:07.000
The horses must keep their heads high.

18:07.000 --> 18:10.000
Horses don't like it.

18:10.000 --> 18:12.000
Says John.

18:12.000 --> 18:17.000
It's very uncomfortable and it hurts their head and neck.

18:17.000 --> 18:19.000
You're right.

18:19.000 --> 18:20.000
Says Mr. York.

18:20.000 --> 18:23.000
But the Lady isn't kind.

18:23.000 --> 18:30.000
I do not know what a bearing rain is, but it sounds terrible.

18:31.000 --> 18:38.000
The next day Ginger and I pull the Lady's carriage and we must wear it.

18:38.000 --> 18:43.000
It is very uncomfortable because we cannot put our heads down.

18:43.000 --> 18:47.000
It is a cruel thing for a horse.

18:47.000 --> 18:50.000
I hate the bearing rain.

18:50.000 --> 18:53.000
Says Ginger one evening.

18:53.000 --> 18:58.000
My head, neck and mouth hurt terribly.

18:58.000 --> 19:03.000
People don't wear it, so they can't understand.

19:03.000 --> 19:07.000
I hate it too, I say.

19:07.000 --> 19:10.000
But what can a poor horse do?

19:10.000 --> 19:13.000
We can do nothing, Beauty.

19:13.000 --> 19:16.000
Says Ginger sadly.

19:16.000 --> 19:20.000
We wear the bearing rain every day.

19:20.000 --> 19:25.000
The Lady comes down the stairs in a beautiful dress and says,

19:25.000 --> 19:35.000
York, take me to the Duchess of Boston and I want the horse's heads high, very high.

19:35.000 --> 19:39.000
She gets into the carriage and sits down.

19:39.000 --> 19:42.000
York prepares Ginger and me.

19:42.000 --> 19:46.000
He comes to me first and pulls the bearing rain.

19:46.000 --> 19:49.000
It feels terrible.

19:49.000 --> 19:53.000
Then he goes to Ginger and does the same.

19:53.000 --> 19:57.000
Ginger gets angry and starts kicking wildly.

19:57.000 --> 20:03.000
York falls to the ground and the Lady in the carriage screams.

20:03.000 --> 20:09.000
Two grooms come from the stable and take poor Ginger away.

20:09.000 --> 20:12.000
She does not ride with me anymore.

20:12.000 --> 20:17.000
The master uses her for the hunts because she is fast.

20:17.000 --> 20:24.000
My new carriage partner is Max, a quiet grey horse.

20:24.000 --> 20:28.000
I think about my old home a lot.

20:28.000 --> 20:35.000
Here I have food and a clean store, but I don't have a lot of friends.

20:35.000 --> 20:43.000
York is a good man, but he is not my friend.

20:43.000 --> 20:49.000
The Royal Society for the Prevention of Cruelty to Animals.

20:49.000 --> 21:00.000
In the 1800s, animals are often mistreated by cruel owners and no one protects them.

21:00.000 --> 21:11.000
In 1824, Richard Martin opens the Society for the Prevention of Cruelty to Animals in London.

21:11.000 --> 21:17.000
It is the first national animal protection society in the world.

21:17.000 --> 21:32.000
In 1840, Queen Victoria gives her permission to call it the Royal Society for the Prevention of Cruelty to Animals, the RSPCA.

21:32.000 --> 21:41.000
People begin to understand that animals are living creatures and it is wrong to mistreat them.

21:41.000 --> 21:51.000
Today, the RSPCA is an important organization with more than 400 inspectors.

21:51.000 --> 21:58.000
They visit homes, pet shops, farms and laboratories.

21:58.000 --> 22:03.000
They work with schools to teach kindness towards animals.

22:03.000 --> 22:10.000
They also work with the government to pass laws that protect animals.

22:10.000 --> 22:24.000
The RSPCA has animal hospitals and centres for abandoned animals all over England and Wales.

22:24.000 --> 22:29.000
Chapter 4 Lizzie

22:29.000 --> 22:33.000
Lady Anne is a friend of Lord Wadsworth's family.

22:33.000 --> 22:38.000
She is young and beautiful and a perfect rider.

22:38.000 --> 22:43.000
I am her favourite horse and I like carrying her.

22:43.000 --> 22:48.000
She is kind to me and always brings me a carrot.

22:48.000 --> 22:53.000
She often rides with her friend, Lord Robert.

22:53.000 --> 22:57.000
He is a handsome young man with dark hair.

22:57.000 --> 23:02.000
He likes horses and often talks to me.

23:02.000 --> 23:07.000
He rides Lizzie, a young, nervous horse.

23:07.000 --> 23:11.000
What a lovely spring day, says Lord Robert.

23:11.000 --> 23:13.000
Let's go riding, Lady Anne.

23:13.000 --> 23:14.000
All right.

23:14.000 --> 23:19.000
She says, but I want to ride your horse today.

23:19.000 --> 23:26.000
Lizzie is a good horse, but she is too nervous for a lady, says Lord Robert.

23:26.000 --> 23:29.000
What nonsense, says Lady Anne.

23:29.000 --> 23:35.000
Today I am riding Lizzie and you are riding black beauty.

23:35.000 --> 23:44.000
Lord Robert is a good rider, but I prefer Lady Anne because she is small and light.

23:44.000 --> 23:49.000
We gallop across the meadows and woods and have a wonderful time.

23:49.000 --> 23:53.000
Then we stop at Dr. Ashley's house.

23:53.000 --> 23:58.000
I must give a letter to the doctor, says Lord Robert.

23:58.000 --> 24:04.000
Lizzie and I can wait here with black beauty, says Lady Anne.

24:04.000 --> 24:08.000
After a few minutes, some cults run by.

24:08.000 --> 24:12.000
Lizzie is nervous and she starts kicking.

24:12.000 --> 24:17.000
Lady Anne is afraid and suddenly Lizzie gallops away.

24:17.000 --> 24:24.000
I know Lizzie is dangerous, so I nay loudly and Lord Robert hears me.

24:24.000 --> 24:27.000
He runs to me and jumps on my back.

24:27.000 --> 24:29.000
Let's go beauty.

24:29.000 --> 24:33.000
He cries, we must help Lady Anne.

24:33.000 --> 24:36.000
We follow Lizzie and Lady Anne.

24:36.000 --> 24:41.000
I gallop quickly because I want to help my mistress.

24:41.000 --> 24:46.000
Lizzie gallops up a hill and down into a valley.

24:46.000 --> 24:54.000
Lady Anne's green hat falls off and her long brown hair flies in the wind.

24:54.000 --> 24:59.000
Then Lizzie jumps across a small river and Lady Anne falls off.

24:59.000 --> 25:02.000
Oh no, cries Lord Robert.

25:02.000 --> 25:07.000
I jump across the river and see my poor mistress on the grass.

25:07.000 --> 25:11.000
Her face is white and her eyes are shut.

25:11.000 --> 25:14.000
She does not move or speak.

25:14.000 --> 25:18.000
Is she dead?

25:18.000 --> 25:22.000
Lady Anne, can you hear me?

25:22.000 --> 25:27.000
asks Lord Robert, but she does not answer.

25:27.000 --> 25:30.000
A young farmer is walking by and says,

25:30.000 --> 25:34.000
To poor lady, can I help her?

25:34.000 --> 25:35.000
Yes.

25:35.000 --> 25:42.000
Says Lord Robert, please go to the village and come back with the doctor.

25:42.000 --> 25:44.000
You can ride my horse beauty.

25:44.000 --> 25:47.000
He's very fast.

25:47.000 --> 25:52.000
The farmer gets on my back and I gallop to the village.

25:52.000 --> 25:56.000
He finds a doctor and we return to Lady Anne.

25:56.000 --> 26:02.000
She is still on the grass and the doctor examines her carefully.

26:02.000 --> 26:05.000
Don't worry, she's not dead.

26:05.000 --> 26:12.000
He says, but we must take her home right now and she must rest.

26:12.000 --> 26:18.000
I feel happy when I hear this because I like my young mistress.

26:18.000 --> 26:24.000
That evening in the stable Ginger and I talk about Lizzie.

26:24.000 --> 26:29.000
Two days later Lord Robert comes to my stall and says,

26:29.000 --> 26:35.000
Lady Anne is better now and she wants to ride you soon.

26:35.000 --> 26:45.000
You are an intelligent horse beauty because you understand a lot of things.

26:45.000 --> 26:51.000
Chapter 5, Ruben Smith

26:51.000 --> 26:56.000
When Mr. York goes to London, Ruben Smith becomes the coachman.

26:56.000 --> 27:02.000
He is a good, honest man and he understands horses.

27:02.000 --> 27:06.000
But he has one big problem.

27:06.000 --> 27:10.000
He drinks a lot and he is often drunk.

27:10.000 --> 27:14.000
One morning he comes to my stall and says,

27:14.000 --> 27:18.000
We're going to town on business beauty.

27:18.000 --> 27:22.000
He puts my saddle on and we go.

27:22.000 --> 27:26.000
When we arrive in town, Smith leaves me at a stable.

27:26.000 --> 27:30.000
My horse is hungry and thirsty.

27:30.000 --> 27:33.000
Says Smith to the stable boy.

27:33.000 --> 27:37.000
I'm coming back at four o'clock.

27:37.000 --> 27:42.000
The boy gives me oats and water and looks at my horseshoes too.

27:42.000 --> 27:47.000
The nails in your front show are loose, he says to me.

27:47.000 --> 27:50.000
You can't run with loose nails.

27:50.000 --> 27:53.000
I must tell Mr. Smith.

27:53.000 --> 28:00.000
But Smith does not come at four o'clock and he does not come at five o'clock.

28:00.000 --> 28:04.000
The boy is worried and I am too.

28:04.000 --> 28:09.000
At nine o'clock in the evening, Smith comes back.

28:09.000 --> 28:13.000
He is angry and his voice is loud.

28:13.000 --> 28:15.000
He cannot walk well.

28:15.000 --> 28:19.000
The front shoe of your horse has loose nails, sir.

28:19.000 --> 28:21.000
Says the boy.

28:21.000 --> 28:25.000
It's dangerous to ride a horse with loose nails.

28:25.000 --> 28:27.000
Smith looks at him and shouts,

28:27.000 --> 28:29.000
It's late.

28:29.000 --> 28:32.000
I'm going home.

28:32.000 --> 28:38.000
It is a dark night and the moon is behind the clouds.

28:38.000 --> 28:40.000
Come on beauty.

28:40.000 --> 28:42.000
Gallop!

28:42.000 --> 28:45.000
He cries and hits me with his whip.

28:45.000 --> 28:50.000
I gallop fast but my front shoe is loose.

28:50.000 --> 28:52.000
I feel the whip again.

28:52.000 --> 28:54.000
Gallop beauty!

28:54.000 --> 28:56.000
Cries Smith again.

28:56.000 --> 29:00.000
At the bridge my front shoe falls off.

29:00.000 --> 29:03.000
My foot hurts a lot.

29:03.000 --> 29:07.000
There are a lot of sharp stones on the road.

29:07.000 --> 29:10.000
I try to gallop but I can't.

29:10.000 --> 29:16.000
At last I fall heavily on my knees and Smith falls off.

29:16.000 --> 29:20.000
I get up slowly and look at Smith.

29:20.000 --> 29:22.000
He is not moving.

29:22.000 --> 29:24.000
What can I do?

29:24.000 --> 29:27.000
Soon I hear Ginger coming.

29:27.000 --> 29:31.000
I nay loudly and she answers.

29:31.000 --> 29:36.000
Then I hear men's voices and they stop in front of Smith.

29:37.000 --> 29:39.000
It's Ruben.

29:39.000 --> 29:41.000
Says one man.

29:41.000 --> 29:43.000
He's dead.

29:43.000 --> 29:44.000
Dead?

29:44.000 --> 29:46.000
Says another man.

29:46.000 --> 29:47.000
Yes.

29:47.000 --> 29:50.000
Says the first man sadly.

29:50.000 --> 29:53.000
Poor Ruben Smith.

29:53.000 --> 29:56.000
Look at his head.

29:56.000 --> 29:59.000
Then the man looks at me.

29:59.000 --> 30:02.000
Look at this poor horse.

30:02.000 --> 30:05.000
It's black beauty.

30:05.000 --> 30:08.000
His knees are badly hurt.

30:08.000 --> 30:14.000
The men slowly take me back to the stable but I cannot sleep.

30:14.000 --> 30:18.000
The next day the vet and the blacksmith come to see me.

30:18.000 --> 30:21.000
Loose horse must rest for a few months.

30:21.000 --> 30:23.000
Says the vet.

30:23.000 --> 30:29.000
So now I stay in the green meadow with its sweet grass.

30:29.000 --> 30:34.000
But I am worried about the future because my knees are not perfect.

30:35.000 --> 30:42.000
After a month Ginger comes to the meadow too because she is very tired.

30:42.000 --> 30:46.000
I like talking to my old friend under the apple tree.

30:46.000 --> 30:52.000
One summer day Lord Wadsworth and York come to the meadow.

30:52.000 --> 30:55.000
They look at my knees.

30:55.000 --> 31:00.000
I'm sorry York but I must sell black beauty.

31:00.000 --> 31:01.000
Says the Lord.

31:01.000 --> 31:05.000
His knees are not perfect anymore.

31:05.000 --> 31:10.000
I can't keep a horse with those knees in my stables.

31:10.000 --> 31:13.000
I'm very sorry because I like beauty.

31:13.000 --> 31:17.000
He's a wonderful horse but his knees.

31:17.000 --> 31:22.000
When they go away Ginger says sadly.

31:22.000 --> 31:28.000
You're the only friend I've got and soon you must leave.

31:28.000 --> 31:32.000
What a difficult life.

31:32.000 --> 31:39.000
I look at her and say Ginger you're my true friend.

31:39.000 --> 31:43.000
The Lord sells me to the town livery stables.

31:43.000 --> 31:46.000
It is not a nice place.

31:46.000 --> 31:51.000
Anyone can hire a horse and carriage at the livery stables.

31:51.000 --> 31:56.000
Most of the drivers are bad and know nothing about horses.

31:56.000 --> 32:01.000
And of course they know nothing about driving a carriage.

32:01.000 --> 32:07.000
They make a lot of mistakes and then get angry with the horse and use the whip.

32:07.000 --> 32:14.000
In the evening I cannot talk about my day because I do not know the other horses.

32:14.000 --> 32:23.000
I am very lonely and think about Ginger.

32:23.000 --> 32:26.000
Listening activity.

32:26.000 --> 32:31.000
Good morning. Is this Jones of stables?

32:31.000 --> 32:33.000
Yes sir. Can I help you?

32:33.000 --> 32:39.000
I'm in town on business today. Can I leave my horse here?

32:39.000 --> 32:41.000
Yes of course.

32:41.000 --> 32:44.000
What time do you close?

32:44.000 --> 32:46.000
We close at 10pm.

32:46.000 --> 32:51.000
Good. I'm coming back at 4pm.

32:51.000 --> 32:55.000
My horse is hungry and thirsty.

32:55.000 --> 32:58.000
How much do oats and water cost?

32:58.000 --> 33:00.000
Four pints sir.

33:00.000 --> 33:03.000
I want to buy some new rains too.

33:03.000 --> 33:07.000
We have brown and black rains.

33:07.000 --> 33:12.000
Good. I want two black rains.

33:12.000 --> 33:14.000
Do you sell blankets too?

33:14.000 --> 33:16.000
No we don't sir.

33:16.000 --> 33:19.000
Where can I buy a blanket for my horse?

33:19.000 --> 33:22.000
At Mr Smith's shop near the town inn.

33:22.000 --> 33:24.000
Where's the town inn?

33:24.000 --> 33:27.000
It's behind the church.

33:27.000 --> 33:31.000
Thank you.

33:31.000 --> 33:37.000
Chapter 6. A London cab horse.

33:37.000 --> 33:43.000
After a year at the livery stables, the master takes me to a horse fair.

33:43.000 --> 33:46.000
He wants to sell me.

33:46.000 --> 33:50.000
A horse fair is an interesting place.

33:50.000 --> 33:54.000
Some of the horses at the fair are young and handsome.

33:54.000 --> 33:58.000
But most of them are old and tired.

33:58.000 --> 34:03.000
Their eyes are sad and they are thin and hungry.

34:03.000 --> 34:09.000
I am still a strong horse but my knees are not perfect anymore.

34:09.000 --> 34:13.000
People come to look at me and they like me.

34:13.000 --> 34:17.000
But when they see my knees, they go away.

34:17.000 --> 34:23.000
At the end of the day, a tall thin man comes and looks at me.

34:23.000 --> 34:26.000
Then he talks to my master.

34:26.000 --> 34:31.000
I'm looking for a gentle horse, he says.

34:31.000 --> 34:36.000
I want to ride him in the fresh air every morning.

34:36.000 --> 34:38.000
This black horse is perfect.

34:38.000 --> 34:40.000
Says my master.

34:40.000 --> 34:42.000
He's very gentle.

34:42.000 --> 34:48.000
My new master is Mr. Barry and he lives in Bath.

34:48.000 --> 34:53.000
He knows nothing about horses but he is a kind man.

34:53.000 --> 35:00.000
He buys a lot of food but the stable boy steals it and takes it home.

35:00.000 --> 35:03.000
He is dishonest and lazy.

35:03.000 --> 35:07.000
He never cleans my feet or my store.

35:07.000 --> 35:11.000
Mr. Barry knows nothing about this.

35:11.000 --> 35:14.000
One day Mr. Barry's friend says,

35:14.000 --> 35:17.000
Your horse is very thin.

35:17.000 --> 35:20.000
What's the matter with him?

35:20.000 --> 35:21.000
I don't know.

35:21.000 --> 35:23.000
Says Mr. Barry.

35:23.000 --> 35:26.000
I always buy a lot of food for him.

35:26.000 --> 35:30.000
Go and see what's happening in the stable.

35:30.000 --> 35:32.000
Says his friend.

35:32.000 --> 35:40.000
My master discovers that the stable boy steals my food and my stall is very dirty.

35:40.000 --> 35:43.000
He is angry and calls the police.

35:43.000 --> 35:48.000
They take the stable boy to prison for two months.

35:48.000 --> 35:53.000
Then Mr. Barry comes to my stall and looks at me sadly.

35:53.000 --> 35:55.000
I'm sorry beauty.

35:55.000 --> 35:56.000
He says.

35:56.000 --> 35:59.000
Let's sell you at the next horse fare.

35:59.000 --> 36:02.000
I'm not lucky with horses.

36:02.000 --> 36:08.000
I am sorry too because I do not like changing masters.

36:08.000 --> 36:15.000
At the next horse fare a short man with kind grey eyes comes to look at me.

36:15.000 --> 36:19.000
He pats my neck gently and smiles.

36:19.000 --> 36:21.000
I like this horse.

36:21.000 --> 36:23.000
He says to the man.

36:23.000 --> 36:27.000
I can pay twenty four pounds for him.

36:27.000 --> 36:28.000
Very well.

36:28.000 --> 36:30.000
The horse is yours.

36:30.000 --> 36:31.000
Says the man.

36:31.000 --> 36:36.000
My new master is a cab driver and lives in London.

36:36.000 --> 36:41.000
His name is Jerry Barker and his wife's name is Polly.

36:41.000 --> 36:46.000
They have got two children, Dolly and Harry.

36:46.000 --> 36:51.000
They are a very happy family and they like me.

36:51.000 --> 36:54.000
Captain is Jerry's other horse.

36:54.000 --> 36:59.000
He is a big white horse and he seems friendly.

36:59.000 --> 37:05.000
Our cab stand is in the center of London and there are many horses.

37:05.000 --> 37:12.000
Jerry is an excellent driver and he never uses the whip or the bearing rain.

37:12.000 --> 37:17.000
Our stable is clean and we are never hungry.

37:17.000 --> 37:21.000
I am lucky to have a kind master.

37:21.000 --> 37:28.000
Sunday is the best day because I can rest all day and talk to Captain.

37:29.000 --> 37:37.000
He is an old military horse and tells me exciting stories about different wars.

37:37.000 --> 37:41.000
The life of a cab horse is difficult.

37:41.000 --> 37:48.000
London is a big city with a lot of noise, people, carriages and cabs.

37:48.000 --> 37:52.000
The weather is often wet and cold.

37:53.000 --> 37:58.000
At the end of the day I am very tired and my knees hurt.

37:58.000 --> 38:02.000
Captain has the same problem.

38:02.000 --> 38:07.000
In the winter Dolly often brings her father a hot lunch.

38:07.000 --> 38:10.000
He eats it at the cab stand.

38:10.000 --> 38:14.000
Jerry's life is difficult too.

38:14.000 --> 38:18.000
One day our cab is waiting outside a park.

38:18.000 --> 38:21.000
Another cab stops next to us.

38:21.000 --> 38:27.000
An old, tired brown horse is pulling the cab.

38:27.000 --> 38:34.000
The poor horse has a long, thin neck and her eyes are almost shut.

38:34.000 --> 38:38.000
I can see her bones through her dirty coat.

38:38.000 --> 38:42.000
She looks at me with her sad eyes and says,

38:42.000 --> 38:46.000
Is that you, Black Beauty?

38:46.000 --> 38:51.000
Ginger, my old friend, I answer.

38:51.000 --> 38:56.000
Yes, it's me, Black Beauty.

38:56.000 --> 38:59.000
It's good to see you.

38:59.000 --> 39:01.000
Says Ginger.

39:01.000 --> 39:03.000
I feel terrible.

39:03.000 --> 39:09.000
I am old, weak, hungry and ill.

39:09.000 --> 39:13.000
I can't run or gallop anymore.

39:13.000 --> 39:21.000
I must pull this heavy cab for my cruel master and I eat very little.

39:21.000 --> 39:26.000
I work all week and never have a day of rest.

39:26.000 --> 39:31.000
Every bone in my old body hurts.

39:31.000 --> 39:34.000
How terrible.

39:34.000 --> 39:38.000
I put my nose near hers.

39:38.000 --> 39:44.000
Dear Ginger, I'm very sorry.

39:44.000 --> 39:50.000
A week later I see a cart with a dead horse in it.

39:50.000 --> 39:53.000
It is Ginger.

39:53.000 --> 39:58.000
I feel very sad when I see her body in the cart.

39:58.000 --> 40:02.000
Why are people cruel to animals?

40:02.000 --> 40:05.000
They do not understand us.

40:05.000 --> 40:12.000
We only want some love and kindness.

40:12.000 --> 40:15.000
Horses.

40:15.000 --> 40:18.000
Horses are beautiful animals.

40:18.000 --> 40:22.000
They are intelligent and friendly.

40:22.000 --> 40:25.000
And they learn quickly too.

40:25.000 --> 40:31.000
Their favorite foods are oats, carrots and apples.

40:31.000 --> 40:35.000
They do not eat meat.

40:35.000 --> 40:39.000
Horses love conversation.

40:39.000 --> 40:45.000
You can talk to a horse and he listens to you happily.

40:45.000 --> 40:48.000
There are three types of horses.

40:48.000 --> 40:53.000
Light, heavy and ponies.

40:53.000 --> 40:57.000
Each kind of horse has a lot of breeds.

40:57.000 --> 41:05.000
Breeds are groups of horses with different colors and sizes.

41:05.000 --> 41:10.000
One, light horses.

41:10.000 --> 41:15.000
They have small bones and thin legs.

41:15.000 --> 41:21.000
And they weigh about 650 kilograms.

41:21.000 --> 41:25.000
Saddle horses are light horses.

41:25.000 --> 41:29.000
People use them for riding.

41:29.000 --> 41:36.000
Some important breeds of saddle horses are thoroughbred horses.

41:36.000 --> 41:43.000
American saddle horses and Arabian stallions.

41:43.000 --> 41:46.000
Quarter horses.

41:46.000 --> 41:51.000
They are fast, strong and intelligent.

41:51.000 --> 41:56.000
They work well with other animals.

41:56.000 --> 42:00.000
The pizana horses.

42:00.000 --> 42:04.000
They are beautiful show horses.

42:04.000 --> 42:10.000
They have a white coat and strong legs.

42:10.000 --> 42:18.000
These horses are part of the Spanish riding school in Vienna, Austria.

42:18.000 --> 42:22.000
It is a very famous riding school.

42:22.000 --> 42:29.000
You can visit it and watch the lippizana horses dance to music.

42:29.000 --> 42:34.000
Two, heavy horses.

42:34.000 --> 42:39.000
They have big bones and big legs.

42:39.000 --> 42:45.000
And they weigh around 1,300 kilograms.

42:45.000 --> 42:52.000
Draft horses are very tall, heavy and strong.

42:52.000 --> 42:58.000
People use them for heavy work and in shows.

42:58.000 --> 43:03.000
Some important breeds of draft horses are

43:03.000 --> 43:13.000
Clyde'sdale horses, Shire horses and Percheron horses.

43:13.000 --> 43:17.000
Three, ponies.

43:17.000 --> 43:24.000
They are small short horses and they weigh around 400 kilograms.

43:24.000 --> 43:27.000
Ponies are gentle.

43:27.000 --> 43:31.000
They are good horses for young riders.

43:31.000 --> 43:35.000
They are strong, clever animals.

43:35.000 --> 43:47.000
Some important breeds of ponies are Shetland ponies, Welsh ponies and Dartmoor ponies.

43:47.000 --> 43:51.000
Horses at work.

43:51.000 --> 43:58.000
Today cars, buses, trains and airplanes take people everywhere.

43:58.000 --> 44:03.000
But horses are still part of our lives.

44:03.000 --> 44:07.000
We ride horses for fun and sport.

44:07.000 --> 44:11.000
We watch them perform at the circus.

44:11.000 --> 44:17.000
People go to the horse races and watch their favorite horse.

44:17.000 --> 44:25.000
Cowboys ride bucking Broncos at rodeos in the United States.

44:25.000 --> 44:32.000
Police men and police women ride horses in big cities like New York City.

44:32.000 --> 44:41.000
Cowboys in North American ranches ride quarter horses when they work with cattle.

44:41.000 --> 44:49.000
A ride in a horse and carriage is a big tourist attraction in some towns and cities.

44:49.000 --> 44:56.000
In poor countries, people use horses to work on farms and to travel.

44:56.000 --> 45:07.000
In some North European countries, horses and ponies pull slays in the snow.

45:07.000 --> 45:13.000
Chapter 7. My Last Home

45:13.000 --> 45:22.000
Christmas and New Year's Eve are happy times for some people but not for cab drivers and their horses.

45:22.000 --> 45:28.000
During that time, we work hard and stay out late.

45:28.000 --> 45:36.000
Often, we must wait for hours in the rain or snow while people are at parties.

45:36.000 --> 45:45.000
On New Year's Eve, Jerry and I take two gentlemen to a party in a big house.

45:45.000 --> 45:53.000
Come back for hours at eleven o'clock and don't be late, says one of the gentlemen.

45:53.000 --> 46:01.000
At eleven o'clock, we are in front of the big house but the gentlemen are not there.

46:01.000 --> 46:07.000
It is a very cold night and it is snowing.

46:07.000 --> 46:16.000
The church bell says it's midnight, says Jerry, but the gentlemen are not here.

46:16.000 --> 46:20.000
We continue to wait in the cold.

46:20.000 --> 46:28.000
At a quarter past one, the door of the big house opens and the two gentlemen come out.

46:28.000 --> 46:34.000
They do not say a word to Jerry and we take them home.

46:34.000 --> 46:40.000
When we get home, Jerry cannot speak and he coughs a lot.

46:40.000 --> 46:46.000
He dries me and puts a warm blanket on my back.

46:46.000 --> 46:51.000
The next morning, Harry comes to give me oats and water.

46:51.000 --> 46:57.000
He pats my neck gently and says, my father is very ill.

46:57.000 --> 47:00.000
He can't drive his cab anymore.

47:00.000 --> 47:03.000
He must find another job.

47:03.000 --> 47:07.000
We must sell you to another cab driver.

47:07.000 --> 47:12.000
I'm very sorry dear old friend.

47:12.000 --> 47:15.000
Dolly comes and kisses me.

47:15.000 --> 47:18.000
Then she starts crying.

47:18.000 --> 47:22.000
Goodbye old friend.

47:22.000 --> 47:27.000
I am very sad to leave Jerry and his family.

47:27.000 --> 47:31.000
My new master is Nicholas Skinner.

47:31.000 --> 47:38.000
He has black eyes and black hair and a loud voice.

47:38.000 --> 47:42.000
He drives an old cab in a bad part of London.

47:42.000 --> 47:47.000
He often whips my back and my head.

47:47.000 --> 47:52.000
He is a cruel master, but I always do my best.

47:52.000 --> 47:59.000
I eat little and work twelve hours a day, seven days a week.

47:59.000 --> 48:04.000
There is no time to rest or to talk to other horses.

48:04.000 --> 48:09.000
My life is very unhappy.

48:09.000 --> 48:16.000
One morning, we go to the railway station and pick up a lady, a man, a young girl,

48:16.000 --> 48:18.000
and a little boy.

48:18.000 --> 48:21.000
They have a lot of heavy luggage.

48:21.000 --> 48:25.000
Skinner puts all the luggage in the cab.

48:25.000 --> 48:29.000
The young girl comes and looks at me.

48:29.000 --> 48:30.000
Father?

48:30.000 --> 48:36.000
She says, this poor horse can't take us and all our luggage.

48:36.000 --> 48:39.000
He is weak and thin.

48:39.000 --> 48:41.000
Please come and look at him.

48:41.000 --> 48:43.000
What nonsense?

48:43.000 --> 48:45.000
Says the man.

48:45.000 --> 48:50.000
Get in the cab at once and be quiet.

48:50.000 --> 48:55.000
I start to pull the heavy cab to Ludgate Hill.

48:55.000 --> 49:00.000
Then I try to climb the hill, but I feel weak.

49:00.000 --> 49:04.000
Suddenly, I fall to the ground.

49:04.000 --> 49:08.000
I try to get up, but I cannot.

49:08.000 --> 49:12.000
How the poor horse cries the young girl.

49:12.000 --> 49:14.000
We are cruel.

49:14.000 --> 49:21.000
A young man throws some cold water on my head, and I slowly get up.

49:21.000 --> 49:27.000
Skinner takes me back to the stables and says, you're working very hard.

49:27.000 --> 49:32.000
Rest for a week, and then I must sell you at the horse fair.

49:32.000 --> 49:36.000
You're not a good horse for my cab.

49:36.000 --> 49:41.000
The horses at the fair are old and tired,

49:41.000 --> 49:45.000
and the people are not rich gentlemen.

49:45.000 --> 49:47.000
They are farmers.

49:47.000 --> 49:52.000
A farmer and his grandson stop in front of me.

49:52.000 --> 49:54.000
Look at this horse, William.

49:54.000 --> 49:56.000
Says the farmer.

49:56.000 --> 50:00.000
He is tired and thin, but he is handsome.

50:00.000 --> 50:02.000
He comes from a good family.

50:02.000 --> 50:05.000
Look at his neck and ears.

50:05.000 --> 50:11.000
The young boy pats my face, and I put my nose in his hand.

50:11.000 --> 50:13.000
Her grandfather.

50:13.000 --> 50:15.000
He likes me.

50:15.000 --> 50:16.000
Says William.

50:16.000 --> 50:18.000
Do you like him?

50:18.000 --> 50:20.000
asks the grandfather.

50:20.000 --> 50:23.000
Yes, I like him a lot.

50:23.000 --> 50:26.000
Says the young boy happily.

50:26.000 --> 50:30.000
The grandfather looks at my teeth and my legs.

50:30.000 --> 50:34.000
Well, I'm buying him for you, William.

50:34.000 --> 50:36.000
Says the grandfather.

50:36.000 --> 50:38.000
You must look after him.

50:38.000 --> 50:42.000
You must feed him and groom him every day.

50:42.000 --> 50:45.000
You can make him feel better.

50:45.000 --> 50:47.000
He is your responsibility.

50:47.000 --> 50:50.000
Oh, thank you, grandfather.

50:50.000 --> 50:53.000
Says William, kissing him.

50:53.000 --> 50:57.000
I promise to look after him.

50:57.000 --> 51:02.000
William and Mr. Turner take me to their stables.

51:02.000 --> 51:08.000
I have a big, clean stall with lots of oats and fresh water.

51:08.000 --> 51:15.000
There is a small meadow outside where I can eat grass and enjoy the sun.

51:15.000 --> 51:18.000
Young William is a perfect master.

51:18.000 --> 51:23.000
Now you must wrasse beauty, says William.

51:23.000 --> 51:28.000
Soon you can run in the meadow with the other horses.

51:29.000 --> 51:34.000
Mr. Turner works on the farm and sometimes he comes to see me.

51:34.000 --> 51:37.000
He looks at my legs and my teeth.

51:37.000 --> 51:41.000
Then he talks to me and gives me some sugar.

51:41.000 --> 51:44.000
Black beauty is feeling better.

51:44.000 --> 51:47.000
Says Mr. Turner to William.

51:47.000 --> 51:50.000
His legs and knees are strong now.

51:50.000 --> 51:54.000
You're doing a good job with this horse.

51:54.000 --> 51:59.000
William smiles and says, thank you, grandfather.

51:59.000 --> 52:02.000
I love black beauty.

52:02.000 --> 52:03.000
I do too.

52:03.000 --> 52:05.000
Says Mr. Turner.

52:05.000 --> 52:08.000
He's a wonderful horse.

52:08.000 --> 52:16.000
The Bloomfield sisters are friends of Mr. Turner and they are looking for a good horse.

52:16.000 --> 52:19.000
Black beauty is feeling fine now.

52:19.000 --> 52:21.000
Says Mr. Turner.

52:21.000 --> 52:26.000
Let's take him to the Bloomfield sisters and see what they say.

52:26.000 --> 52:28.000
Yes, grandfather.

52:28.000 --> 52:29.000
Says William.

52:29.000 --> 52:33.000
What a good idea.

52:33.000 --> 52:40.000
One summer day, William and Mr. Turner take me to visit their friends.

52:40.000 --> 52:45.000
Ellen Bloomfield and her two sisters are happy when they see me.

52:45.000 --> 52:50.000
This horse has a good face and he's very handsome.

52:50.000 --> 52:51.000
Says Ellen.

52:51.000 --> 52:53.000
I like him.

52:53.000 --> 52:55.000
Can I try him for a week?

52:55.000 --> 52:57.000
Yes, of course.

52:57.000 --> 53:00.000
Says Mr. Turner happily.

53:00.000 --> 53:06.000
A stable boy takes me to a big stable and starts grooming me.

53:06.000 --> 53:13.000
Every morning he comes to my store and pats me and talks to me.

53:13.000 --> 53:15.000
Good morning beauty.

53:15.000 --> 53:19.000
He says, what a lovely day.

53:19.000 --> 53:23.000
Then go to the meadow today.

53:23.000 --> 53:27.000
He grooms me and gives me an apple.

53:27.000 --> 53:30.000
Then he takes me to the meadow.

53:30.000 --> 53:35.000
I like the tall trees and the beautiful flowers.

53:35.000 --> 53:39.000
I feel better every day.

53:39.000 --> 53:43.000
This is the same star black beauty has.

53:43.000 --> 53:48.000
Says the young man, looking at the white star on my face.

53:48.000 --> 53:53.000
And this is the same white foot too.

53:53.000 --> 53:59.000
He looks at my back and sees a little white spot.

53:59.000 --> 54:03.000
Oh, this is black beauty.

54:03.000 --> 54:05.000
He cries.

54:05.000 --> 54:07.000
Black beauty.

54:07.000 --> 54:09.000
Do you remember me?

54:09.000 --> 54:16.000
I'm Joe Green, the stable boy at Mr. Gordon's.

54:16.000 --> 54:20.000
I put my nose in his hand.

54:20.000 --> 54:24.000
Yes, it is Joe Green.

54:24.000 --> 54:29.000
He is very happy and tells the Blomfield sisters about me.

54:29.000 --> 54:35.000
They are happy too and they want to keep me forever.

54:35.000 --> 54:39.000
Now I am part of the Blomfield family.

54:39.000 --> 54:45.000
Ellen writes me almost every day and I am her favorite horse.

54:45.000 --> 54:50.000
Sometimes I take her sisters to town in the carriage.

54:50.000 --> 54:57.000
My good friends Mr. Turner and William often come to visit me.

54:57.000 --> 55:12.000
I am finally happy in this wonderful home because everyone loves me and I love them.

55:12.000 --> 55:15.000
Listening activity.

55:15.000 --> 55:20.000
Ellen and Mr. Turner meet at the bakers.

55:20.000 --> 55:25.000
Ellen is buying biscuits and a chocolate cake.

55:25.000 --> 55:30.000
Hello Mr. Turner, it's good to see you.

55:30.000 --> 55:34.000
Hello Ellen, nice to see you too.

55:34.000 --> 55:37.000
Are you looking for a good horse?

55:37.000 --> 55:41.000
Yes, I'm looking for a gentle horse.

55:41.000 --> 55:44.000
I have a wonderful horse for you.

55:44.000 --> 55:50.000
His name is Black Beauty and he's five years old.

55:50.000 --> 55:54.000
He's very gentle and he's perfect for a lady.

55:54.000 --> 55:57.000
When can I see him?

55:57.000 --> 56:02.000
I can bring him to your house next week on Tuesday.

56:02.000 --> 56:04.000
That's good.

56:04.000 --> 56:07.000
Come in the morning before lunch.

56:07.000 --> 56:09.000
Where do you live?

56:09.000 --> 56:13.000
I live in the big white house near the river.

56:13.000 --> 56:17.000
How much does the horse cost?

56:17.000 --> 56:23.000
I can sell him to you for eighteen pounds.

